---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Navigation from '@/components/Navigation.astro';
import Footer from '@/components/Footer.astro';
import { BookOpen, AlertTriangle, CheckCircle } from 'lucide-astro';
---

<Layout title="How to Measure Concrete Slump | Testing Guide | Toronto Concrete">
  <Navigation />
  
  <main>
    <!-- Hero Section -->
    <section class="bg-gray-100 pt-24 pb-12">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
            <a href="/" class="hover:text-red-600">Home</a>
            <span>/</span>
            <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-red-600">Blog</a>
            <span>/</span>
            <span>Concrete Slump Test</span>
          </div>
          <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
            How to Measure Concrete Slump
          </h1>
          <p class="text-xl text-gray-600">
            A complete guide to slump testing for quality concrete
          </p>
          <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mt-4 text-sm text-gray-500">
            <span>Published: January 2024</span>
            <span>•</span>
            <span>10 min read</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <article class="py-12">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <!-- Introduction -->
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 mb-8">
              The slump test is the most common way to measure concrete workability on site. It tells us if the 
              concrete mix has the right consistency for proper placement and finishing. Too wet? You'll have weak 
              concrete. Too dry? It won't flow properly. Here's everything you need to know about slump testing.
            </p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">What is Slump?</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              Slump measures how much fresh concrete "slumps" or settles when a cone-shaped mold is removed. 
              It's measured in millimeters (or inches) and indicates the concrete's workability - essentially 
              how easy it is to pour, place, and finish.
            </p>

            <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Typical Slump Ranges</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                <li><strong>0-25mm (0-1"):</strong> Very dry, used for road construction with machine placement</li>
                <li><strong>25-50mm (1-2"):</strong> Low slump, for foundations with minimal reinforcement</li>
                <li><strong>50-100mm (2-4"):</strong> Medium slump, standard for footings and slabs</li>
                <li><strong>100-150mm (4-6"):</strong> High slump, for walls and columns with heavy reinforcement</li>
                <li><strong>150mm+ (6"+):</strong> Very high slump, pumped concrete or self-consolidating</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Equipment Needed -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Equipment for Slump Test</h2>
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-8 border border-gray-200">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Standard Equipment (ASTM C143)</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                  <div>
                    <strong>Slump Cone:</strong> Metal cone 300mm (12") high, 200mm (8") bottom diameter, 
                    100mm (4") top diameter
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                  <div>
                    <strong>Tamping Rod:</strong> 16mm (5/8") diameter, 600mm (24") long, rounded tip
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                  <div>
                    <strong>Base Plate:</strong> Flat, non-absorbent surface, minimum 400mm x 400mm
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                  <div>
                    <strong>Ruler/Tape:</strong> For measuring the slump (300mm or 12" minimum)
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                  <div>
                    <strong>Scoop:</strong> For filling the cone with concrete
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Step by Step Process -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Step-by-Step Slump Test Procedure</h2>
            
            <div class="space-y-6">
              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">1</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Prepare Equipment</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Dampen the cone and base plate with water. Place cone on level base plate and stand on foot pieces 
                      to hold it steady. The cone must not move during filling.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">2</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Fill First Layer</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Fill cone 1/3 full (approximately 70mm or 2.75" deep). Rod this layer 25 times with the tamping 
                      rod, distributing strokes evenly. Penetrate entire depth of layer.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">3</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Fill Second Layer</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Fill cone 2/3 full (approximately 160mm or 6.25" from bottom). Rod 25 times, penetrating slightly 
                      into first layer (about 25mm or 1"). Distribute strokes evenly.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">4</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Fill Third Layer</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Overfill the cone slightly. Rod 25 times, penetrating slightly into second layer. Keep concrete 
                      above top of cone throughout rodding.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">5</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Strike Off Surface</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Use tamping rod to strike off excess concrete level with top of cone. Use a rolling motion. 
                      Clean any spillage from around base of cone.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">6</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Lift Cone</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Carefully lift cone straight up in 5±2 seconds. Do not twist or move laterally. The lift must 
                      be smooth and continuous.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
                <div class="flex gap-4">
                  <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 font-bold">7</div>
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Measure Slump</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                      Immediately measure the difference between the height of the cone (300mm) and the highest point 
                      of the slumped concrete. Record to nearest 5mm (1/4").
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8 border-2 border-yellow-400">
              <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
                <AlertTriangle class="w-5 h-5 text-yellow-600" />
                Important Timing
              </h3>
              <p class="text-gray-700">
                The entire test from start of filling to removal of cone should be completed within 2.5 minutes. 
                Test must be done within 5 minutes of obtaining the concrete sample.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Types of Slump -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Types of Slump Results</h2>
            
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">True Slump ✓</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
                  Concrete slumps evenly all around, maintaining general cone shape. This is the only valid result.
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-green-600 font-semibold">
                  Valid test - record measurement
                </p>
              </div>
              
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Shear Slump ⚠</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
                  One side of cone shears off and slips down. Common with low-slump concrete.
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-yellow-600 font-semibold">
                  Retest with fresh sample
                </p>
              </div>
              
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Collapse Slump ✗</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
                  Concrete completely collapses. Indicates very high slump (>200mm) or poor mix.
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-red-600 font-semibold">
                  Mix too wet - reject or adjust
                </p>
              </div>
              
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-200">
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Zero Slump ✗</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
                  No measurable slump. Concrete is too dry for the test method.
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-red-600 font-semibold">
                  Use different test method
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Common Applications -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Recommended Slumps for Different Applications</h2>
            
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-gray-200">
              <table class="w-full">
                <thead class="bg-gray-50">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-bold text-gray-900">Application</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-bold text-gray-900">Slump Range</th>
                    <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-bold text-gray-900">Notes</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Footings & Foundations</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">75-125mm (3-5")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-sm text-gray-600">Standard residential</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Slabs on Grade</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">75-100mm (3-4")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-sm text-gray-600">Driveways, garage floors</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Walls & Columns</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">100-150mm (4-6")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-sm text-gray-600">Heavy reinforcement</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Pumped Concrete</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">125-175mm (5-7")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-sm text-gray-600">Must flow through pump</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">Mass Concrete</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-700">25-75mm (1-3")</td>
                    <td class="py-3 px-4 text-sm text-gray-600">Large foundations</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Factors Affecting Slump -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Factors That Affect Slump</h2>
            
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Increases Slump:</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-red-600">↑</span>
                    More water content
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-red-600">↑</span>
                    Higher temperature
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-red-600">↑</span>
                    Water-reducing admixtures
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-red-600">↑</span>
                    Rounded aggregates
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-red-600">↑</span>
                    Time since mixing
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Decreases Slump:</h3>
                <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-blue-600">↓</span>
                    Less water content
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-blue-600">↓</span>
                    Lower temperature
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-blue-600">↓</span>
                    Higher cement content
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-blue-600">↓</span>
                    Angular aggregates
                  </li>
                  <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="text-blue-600">↓</span>
                    Air-entraining admixtures
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Field Tips -->
          <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-8 mb-12 border-2 border-red-200">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Field Tips from 39 Years Experience</h2>
            
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                <span>
                  <strong>Test early:</strong> Always test the first truck. If slump is wrong, you can adjust 
                  subsequent trucks.
                </span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                <span>
                  <strong>Sample correctly:</strong> Take sample from middle portion of load, not first or last 
                  discharge.
                </span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                <span>
                  <strong>Temperature matters:</strong> Hot weather increases slump loss. Test more frequently 
                  in summer.
                </span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                <span>
                  <strong>Don't add water:</strong> Never add water on site to increase slump - it weakens the 
                  concrete. Use plasticizers instead.
                </span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <CheckCircle class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600 mt-0.5" />
                <span>
                  <strong>Document everything:</strong> Record slump, time, temperature, truck number, and location 
                  placed.
                </span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <!-- Conclusion -->
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Why Slump Testing Matters</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              Proper slump ensures your concrete is workable enough to place and finish properly, while maintaining 
              the strength needed for long-term durability. At Toronto Concrete, we test every load to ensure 
              consistent quality.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              Remember: slump is just one measure of concrete quality. Proper mix design, air content, temperature, 
              and curing are equally important for strong, durable concrete that lasts decades.
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- CTA -->
          <div class="bg-gray-900 text-white rounded-lg p-8 mt-12 text-center">
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Need Professional Concrete Work?</h3>
            <p class="text-lg mb-6">
              We handle all the technical details - you just enjoy the results
            </p>
            <a href="tel:437-545-0067" class="inline-block bg-red-600 text-white px-8 py-3 rounded-lg font-semibold hover:bg-red-700 transition-colors">
              Call: (437) 545-0067
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>